{
  "terms": [
    {
      "term": "TT System",
      "simpleDefinition": "An earthing arrangement where the consumer provides their own connection to Earth, usually via a rod in the ground.",
      "anchor": "The 'local rod' system.",
      "misconception": "Thinking the supplier provides the earth connection in a TT system; they only provide the live and neutral."
    },
    {
      "term": "TN-S System",
      "simpleDefinition": "An earthing arrangement where the supplier provides a separate earth conductor (often the cable sheath) all the way from the transformer.",
      "anchor": "The 'separate earth' system.",
      "misconception": "Confusing it with TN-C-S because both use the supplier's cable for earth."
    },
    {
      "term": "TN-C-S System",
      "simpleDefinition": "An earthing arrangement where the supplier's neutral and earth are combined in one conductor before being split at the property intake.",
      "anchor": "The 'combined then separate' system.",
      "misconception": "Thinking the earth and neutral stay combined inside the building's internal circuits."
    },
    {
      "term": "ADS (Automatic Disconnection of Supply)",
      "simpleDefinition": "A safety strategy that uses earthing and protective devices to automatically cut power during a fault.",
      "anchor": "The 'safety trip' system.",
      "misconception": "Believing ADS is a single part; it is actually a system of multiple components working together."
    },
    {
      "term": "CPC (Circuit Protective Conductor)",
      "simpleDefinition": "The specific wire in a circuit that connects metal parts to the main earthing terminal.",
      "anchor": "The 'circuit earth wire'.",
      "misconception": "Using the term CPC to describe the main earthing conductor that connects to the supplier."
    },
    {
      "term": "Earthing Conductor",
      "simpleDefinition": "The main wire that connects the installation's earthing terminal to the supplier's earth or an electrode.",
      "anchor": "The 'main earth link'.",
      "misconception": "Thinking this is the same as a CPC; the earthing conductor serves the whole installation, not just one circuit."
    },
    {
      "term": "Main Protective Bonding",
      "simpleDefinition": "Conductors that connect metal services like water or gas pipes to the main earthing terminal.",
      "anchor": "The 'pipe bonding' wire.",
      "misconception": "Thinking bonding is designed to carry fault current from a broken appliance; its job is to keep metalwork at the same voltage."
    },
    {
      "term": "Earth Electrode",
      "simpleDefinition": "A metal rod or plate buried in the ground to provide a physical connection to the Earth.",
      "anchor": "The 'ground rod'.",
      "misconception": "Believing every house needs an electrode; they are primarily used for TT systems."
    },
    {
      "term": "Protective Device",
      "simpleDefinition": "A component such as a fuse or circuit breaker that breaks the circuit when it detects a fault.",
      "anchor": "The 'circuit breaker or fuse'.",
      "misconception": "Thinking the earth wire itself 'blows' to stop the fault; the wire provides the path, but the device does the disconnecting."
    }
  ],
  "anchorPhrases": [
    "TT uses a local rod",
    "TN-S has a separate earth throughout",
    "TN-C-S combines neutral and earth in the supply",
    "ADS requires a complete path and a protective device",
    "The CPC is for the circuit, the Earthing Conductor is for the whole system"
  ],
  "misconceptionTargets": [
    "Terms in this lesson are distinct and must be used precisely.",
    "TN-S and TN-C-S are different because of how the supplier's cable is constructed.",

{
  "teachChecks": [
    {
      "title": "Earthing System Types",
      "objective": "Identify and distinguish between TT, TN-S, and TN-C-S earthing systems.",
      "retrievalTextLines": [
        "Earthing systems are identified by letter codes that describe the connection between the power source and the installation. The first letter 'T' stands for Terre (French for Earth), meaning the source is connected directly to Earth. The second letter 'N' stands for Neutral, meaning the installation's metalwork is connected to the supplier's neutral conductor.",
        "In a TN-S system, the 'S' stands for Separate. This means the Neutral and Earth are separate conductors all the way from the transformer to the property. In a TN-C-S system, the 'C' stands for Combined. Here, the supplier uses one single conductor for both Neutral and Earth (called a PEN conductor) until it reaches the property, where it is split into two separate terminals.",
        "A TT system has a second 'T', meaning the consumer provides their own connection to Earth. Because the supplier does not provide an earth terminal in a TT system, the installer must drive an Earth Electrode, such as a metal rod, into the ground to create a local connection to Earth."
      ],
      "hint": "Focus on what the letters S (Separate), C (Combined), and the second T (Terre/Local Earth) represent regarding the path back to the source."
    },
    {
      "title": "ADS Component Parts",
      "objective": "Identify the specific components that make up an ADS system.",
      "retrievalTextLines": [
        "Automatic Disconnection of Supply (ADS) is a safety strategy that uses several components to cut power during a fault. The Earthing Conductor is the main wire that connects the installation's main earthing terminal to the supplier's earth or a local electrode. From this central terminal, a Circuit Protective Conductor (CPC) runs to every individual circuit. The CPC provides a dedicated path for fault current to flow safely from an appliance back to the consumer unit.",
        "Main Protective Bonding conductors are used to connect metal service pipes, such as gas and water, to the main earthing terminal. This is done to keep all accessible metalwork at the same voltage, preventing electric shocks if a fault occurs elsewhere. Supplementary Bonding may also be used for extra safety in high-risk areas like bathrooms.",
        "The final component is the Protective Device, which is a fuse or circuit breaker. When a fault occurs, the earthing path (CPC and Earthing Conductor) allows a high current to flow. This high current causes the Protective Device to trip or blow, which automatically disconnects the power supply to stop the danger."
      ],
      "hint": "Remember that the CPC serves individual circuits, while the Earthing Conductor is the single main link to the earth source."
    }
  ]
}

