{
  "integrative": {
    "title": "Integrative Close",
    "objective": "Synthesize the relationship between the earthing system type and the specific hardware required to complete the ADS path.",
    "retrievalTextLines": [
      "Automatic Disconnection of Supply (ADS) only works if there is a complete path for fault current to travel back to the source. In TN-S and TN-C-S systems, the supplier provides this path through their cabling.",
      "In a TT system, the supplier does not provide an earth return path. This means the installer must create a local connection to the mass of Earth to ensure that if a fault occurs, the protective device can still detect the current and trip."
    ],
    "questionText": "In a TT system installation, explain the specific purpose of the Earth Electrode in relation to ADS, and identify the name of the conductor that links this electrode to the Main Earthing Terminal (MET).",
    "answerGuidance": [
      "The Earth Electrode provides a local connection to the ground to create a return path for fault current because the supplier does not provide one. The conductor used to link it to the MET is the Earthing Conductor.",
      "It creates a path to earth so the protective device can trip. The link is the Earthing Conductor."
    ],
    "hint": "Think about why you need a rod in the ground if the supplier hasn't given you an earth wire, and remember the specific name for the 'main link' between the earth source and the consumer unit."
  }
